{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17492790","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17492790"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T06:45:20+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T06:45:20+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1156"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1156","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1156"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.05,0.11,0.17,0.49,0.18]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1156"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"52496"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1156","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1156"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1156"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"37853"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"5"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"93"},{"type":"tags","id":"3476"},{"type":"tags","id":"4578"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"6381"},{"type":"contributions","id":"6743"},{"type":"contributions","id":"14443"},{"type":"contributions","id":"14821"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"52496","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/52496"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 25-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic with a two-day history of cramping abdominal pain. He has had loose stools and lost about 5 kg body weight over the last eight weeks. He feels increasingly fatigued.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHe has a medical history of Crohn\u0027s disease confined to the terminal ileum and colon, diagnosed eight months ago. He was initially treated with azathioprine and prednisone, which induced remission of his symptoms. The prednisone was subsequently weaned and ceased. When his symptoms returned, he was commenced on another course of prednisone and continues on 15 mg daily. He has no other significant medical history and takes no other regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well. His pulse rate is 72/min, blood pressure 120/80 mmHg, respiratory rate 14/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 36.8\u00b0C. Abdominal examination is unremarkable. An MRI small bowel shows persisting inflammation in the terminal ileum consistent with active Crohn\u0027s disease.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate approach to long-term management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Budesonide","Mercaptopurine","Methotrexate","Adalimumab","Ileal resection"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with a relapse of Crohn\u0027s disease despite being on an immunomodulator (azathioprine) and previous steroid treatment. His symptoms suggest moderate to severe disease activity, indicating the need for a step-up approach in treatment.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAdalimumab\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate choice for long-term management in this scenario. It is an anti-TNF biologic agent that has been shown to be effective in inducing and maintaining remission in moderate to severe Crohn\u0027s disease. Biologics like adalimumab are particularly useful when patients have failed or had an inadequate response to conventional therapies, as in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBudesonide\u003C/strong\u003E is not suitable for long-term management of Crohn\u0027s disease. While it\u0027s often used for inducing remission during mild to moderate flares, particularly in ileal disease, prolonged use is still associated with side effects and not recommended. The goal is to taper and discontinue steroids once remission is achieved.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMercaptopurine\u003C/strong\u003E is another immunomodulator similar to azathioprine. While it can be effective in maintaining remission, the recurrence of symptoms suggests that the current regimen of steroids and immunomodulatory agent is not providing adequate control in this case, necessitating escalation of therapy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMethotrexate\u003C/strong\u003E is another immunomodulator used in Crohn\u0027s disease. While it can be effective in maintaining remission, it is generally considered less potent than biologics like adalimumab for inducing remission in moderate to severe disease.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIleal resection\u003C/strong\u003E is not appropriate as a first-line approach for long-term management in this case. Surgery is typically reserved for complications such as strictures, fistulas, or abscesses, or for patients who have failed medical management. In this case, medical management options have not been exhausted.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn managing Crohn\u0027s disease, the goal is to induce and maintain remission while minimizing corticosteroid use. Biologic agents like adalimumab have revolutionized the treatment of inflammatory bowel diseases by targeting specific inflammatory pathways. They are particularly valuable in patients with moderate to severe disease or those who have failed conventional therapies.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Biologics play an important role in the long-term management of Crohn\u0027s disease.","Anti-TNF agents like adalimumab are effective for inducing and maintaining remission in moderate to severe Crohn\u0027s disease.","Corticosteroids are not appropriate for long-term management of Crohn\u0027s disease due to side effects."],"references":["Sands BE, Irving PM, Hoops T, at al. Ustekinumab versus adalimumab for induction and maintenance therapy in biologic-naive patients with moderately to severely active Crohn\u2019s disease: a multicentre, randomised, double-blind, parallel-group, phase 3b trial. Lancet 2022; 399: 2200\u201311.","Ford AC, Sandborn WJ, Khan KJ, Hanauer SB, Talley NJ, Moayyedi P. Efficacy of biological therapies in inflammatory bowel disease: systematic review and meta-analysis. Am J Gastroenterol. 2011 Apr;106(4):644-59, quiz 660. doi: 10.1038/ajg.2011.73. Epub 2011 Mar 15. PMID: 21407183."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"37853"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1156"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"37853","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/37853"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-09-06T11:39:05+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-09-06T11:43:29+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1156"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"52496"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"5","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/5"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2d","name":"Gastroenterology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical studen